[5] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Sat 26 Mar 2011
Source: Tweed Dally News [edited]
<http://www.tweednews.com.au/story/2011/03/26/measles-may-have-been-spread-at-shops-helensvale/>


A 2nd measles case has been confirmed on the Gold Coast, following
the 1st outbreak at the end of February 2011. Queensland Health is
urging anyone who was at the Westfield Helensvale shopping centre from
10 to 18 Mar 2011 to be alert for symptoms after the confirmation of
measles in a person working at the centre during this period. Gold
Coast Public Health medical officer, Dr Don Staines, said the person
had no history of overseas or interstate travel, and no obvious link
to the 1st case reported on the Gold Coast.

Anyone who develops measles-like symptoms should contact their GP.
"It's very important to call the medical practice 1st to say you could
have measles, so that staff can take precautions to avoid spreading
the disease to others," he said. Dr Staines said symptoms usually
started about 10 days after infection. "Measles can be very
distressing for those affected, and complications can include
pneumonia or encephalitis (inflammation of the brain) and occasionally
death," he said. "Queensland Health will continue to actively
investigate this case and do whatever it can to prevent further
transmission."

